and convert the ester to allyl ester. Specifically:\n- Replace H on C3 with CH3 (alkylation)\n- Replace one H on CH2 of -CH2COOMe with... wait, this doesn't make sense.\n\nLet me reconsider. After Stork alkylation, C3 has:\n- C2 (ring)\n- C4 (ring)  \n- H\n- CH2COOMe\n\nFor the target, C3 needs:\n- C2 (ring)\n- C4 (ring)\n- CH3\n- COOAllyl\n\nSo I need to:\n1. Replace the H on C3 with CH3\n2. Replace the CH2 in -CH2COOMe with just a direct bond to COOAllyl\n\nThis means I need to:\n1. Alkylate C3 with MeI (replace H with CH3)\n2. Somehow convert -CH2COOMe to -COOAllyl\n\nStep 2 doesn't make sense chemically. -CH2COOMe can't be converted to -COOAllyl by any simple transformation.\n\nI think the issue is that the Stork enamine alkylation with BrCH2COOMe gives the wrong connectivity. The product has -CH2COOMe (a 2-carbon chain from C3 to the ester), but the target has -COOAllyl (a 1-carbon connection from C3 to the ester).\n\nSo the Stork enamine approach with BrCH2COOMe doesn't give the right product. I need a different approach.\n\nWhat if I use methyl chloroformate (ClCOOMe, 2 carbons ✓) instead of methyl bromoacetate?\n\nStork enamine alkylation with methyl chloroformate:\n\nThe enamine of 1,4-cyclohexanedione attacks ClCOOMe:\n\nProduct: C3 has -COOMe directly attached (no CH2 spacer).\n\nSo the product would be: 3,6-bis(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione\n\nThis has -COOMe at C3 and C6, which means C3 is bonded to: C2, C4, H, and COOMe.\n\nFor the target, C3 needs: C2, C4, CH3, and COOAllyl.\n\nSo I need to:\n1. Replace the H on C3 with CH3 (alkylation with MeI)\n2. Convert COOMe to COOAllyl (ester exchange)\n\nThis works! Let me flesh out the route:\n\nStep 1: Succinic acid → 1,4-cyclohexanedione\nStep 2: 1,4-Cyclohexanedione + pyrrolidine → bis-enamine\nStep 3: Bis-enamine + 2 equiv methyl chloroformate → 3,6-bis(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione (after hydrolysis)\nStep 4: 3,6-bis(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione + 2 equiv LDA, then 2 equiv MeI → 3,6-dimethyl-3,6-bis(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione\nStep 5: Ester exchange with allyl alcohol (acid catalyst) → 3,6-dimethyl-3,6-bis(allyloxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione (target)\n\nWait, but in step 3, the Stork enamine alkylation with methyl chloroformate... is this a known reaction? Stork enamine alkylation typically works with alkyl halides. Methyl chloroformate is an acylating agent, not an alkylating agent.\n\nWhen an enamine reacts with an acyl chloride (or chloroformate), it gives an acylated product (C-acylation), which after hydrolysis gives a β-ketoester or β-dicarbonyl compound.\n\nSo the enamine of 1,4-cyclohexanedione + methyl chloroformate would give:\n\nC-acylation at C3: the enamine carbon attacks the carbonyl of ClCOOMe, giving an iminium intermediate that hydrolyzes to give a β-ketoester.\n\nProduct: 3-(methoxycarbonyl)-4-cyclohexanedione? No, that's not right.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The enamine at C3 of 1,4-cyclohexanedione:\n\nThe enamine has the structure: C2=C3-NR2 (with C1=O and C4=O as the flanking ketones)\n\nWhen this enamine attacks ClCOOMe:\n\nC2=C3-NR2 + Cl-C(=O)-OCH3 → C2=C3(-C(=O)-OCH3)-NR2⁺Cl⁻\n\nAfter hydrolysis: C2(H)-C3(-C(=O)-OCH3) with C1=O and C4=O\n\nSo C3 now has: C2, C4, H, and -C(=O)OCH3\n\nThis is 3-(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione. But wait, C3 is α to both C1=O and C4=O, and now it also has a -C(=O)OCH3 group. This makes C3 a 1,3-dicarbonyl carbon (with C4=O and -C(=O)OCH3), which means it's quite acidic.\n\nFor the bis-acylation, we'd get: 3,6-bis(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione\n\nThis compound has -COOMe at C3 and C6. C3 is α to C4=O (and also to C1=O in a 1,3-relationship), and it has a -COOMe group. So C3 is part of a β-ketoester system (C4=O and -COOMe are in a 1,3-relationship through C3).\n\nNow, for step 4, we need to alkylate C3 with MeI. But C3 is part of a β-ketoester, so it's very acidic. Deprotonation with base (LDA or NaH) and alkylation with MeI should work.\n\nProduct: 3-methyl-3-(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione (at one position), and similarly at C6.\n\nSo the product is: 3,6-dimethyl-3,6-bis(methoxycarbonyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione\n\nThen step 5: ester exchange with allyl alcohol gives the target.\n\nThis route seems viable! But I need to verify step 1 (making 1,4-cyclohexanedione from succinic acid).\n\nHow to make 1,4-cyclohexanedione from succinic acid:\n\nMethod 1: Via Stork enamine synthesis\n- Succinic acid → succinyl chloride (SOCl2)\n- Succinyl chloride + 2 equiv enamine of acetaldehyde → 1,4-cyclohexanedione\n\nBut as I analyzed earlier, this gives a linear product that needs to cyclize. Let me reconsider.\n\nSuccinyl chloride + 2 equiv enamine of acetaldehyde:\n\nFirst enamine attacks one acyl chloride:\nCH2=CH-NR2 + ClOC-CH2CH2-COCl → OHC-CH2-CO-CH2CH2-COCl (after hydrolysis)\n\nWait, the enamine of acetaldehyde is CH2=CH-NR2. The nucleophilic carbon (the terminal CH2) attacks the acyl chloride:\n\n⁻CH2-CH=NR2 + Cl-CO-CH2CH2-COCl → CH2(-CO-CH2CH2-COCl)-CH=NR2⁺\n\nAfter hydrolysis: CH2(-CO-CH2CH2-COCl)-CHO = OHC-CH2-CO-CH2CH2-COCl\n\nThis is 4-chloro-4-oxobutanoylacetaldehyde... hmm, this is 3-oxo-7-chloro-7-oxoheptanal.\n\nThen second enamine attacks:\nOHC-CH2-CO-CH2CH2-COCl + CH2=CH-NR2 → OHC-CH2-CO-CH2CH2-CO-CH2-CHO (after hydrolysis)\n\nThis is 3,6-dioxooctanedial.\n\nNow, intramolecular aldol cyclization: the enolate of one aldehyde attacks the other aldehyde (or a ketone).\n\nFor a 6-membered ring, the enolate of C1 (aldehyde) attacks C6 (ketone):\nRing: C1-C2-C3-C4-C5-C6 → 6-membered ring ✓\n\nProduct: 2-(2-oxoethyl)cyclohexane-1,4-dione? No, let me think again.\n\nOHC-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CHO\nC1  C2  C3  C4  C5  C6  C7  C8\n\nEnolate at C8 (aldehyde) attacks C3 (ketone):\nRing: C3-C4-C5-C6-C7-C8 → 6-membered ring ✓\n\nProduct: a 6-membered ring with C3, C4, C5, C6, C7, C8, where C3 has an OH (from aldol), and C8 is bonded to C3.\n\nAfter dehydration: 2-formylmethyl-2-cyclohexen-1-one? This is getting complicated.\n\nActually, I think the standard synthesis of 1,4-cyclohexanedione from succinic acid doesn't go through succinyl chloride + enamine. Let me look for a different method.\n\nMethod 2: Via Diels-Alder\n- Succinic acid → maleic anhydride (isomerization and dehydration)... but maleic anhydride is the cis-isomer of succinic anhydride, and succinic anhydride is not a dienophile.\n\nActually, maleic anhydride + 1,3-butadiene → Diels-Alder → cis-4-cyclohexene-1,2-dicarboxylic anhydride. But this gives a 1,2-dicarboxylic acid, not a 1,4-diketone.\n\nMethod 3: Via reduction\n- Succinic acid → 1,4-butanediol (LiAlH4)\n- 1,4-Butanediol → 1,4-dibromobutane (PBr3)\n- 1,4-Dibromobutane + 2 equiv enolate of acetaldehyde → 1,4-cyclohexanedione? \n\nHmm, this doesn't work directly.\n\nMethod 4: Via double Stork enamine alkylation\n- Succinic acid → 1,4-dibromobutane (via 1,4-butanediol)\n- 2 equiv enamine of acetaldehyde + 1,4-dibromobutane → double alkylation → 1,4-cyclohexanedione (after hydrolysis)\n\nWait, this could work! The bis-enamine of acetaldehyde (2 equiv) reacts with 1,4-dibromobutane in a double alkylation:\n\nCH2=CH-NR2 + BrCH2CH2CH2CH2Br → ring formation?\n\nNo, with 2 separate molecules of enamine and a 1,4-dibromobutane, we'd get:\n\nCH2=CH-NR2 attacks one end of BrCH2CH2CH2CH2Br:\n→ CH2(-CH2CH2CH2CH2Br)-CH=NR2⁺ → after hydrolysis: OHC-CH2-CH2CH2CH2CH2Br\n\nThen the second enamine attacks:\n→ OHC-CH2-CH2CH2CH2CH2-CH2-CHO = 1,8-octanedial\n\nThis is a linear dialdehyde, not a cyclic compound. For cyclization, we'd need an intramolecular reaction.\n\nHmm, this doesn't directly give 1,4-cyclohexanedione.\n\nOK, I think I need to accept that making 1,4-cyclohexanedione from succinic acid is a multi-step process and move on with the overall route.\n\nActually, here's a known synthesis of 1,4-cyclohexanedione from succinic acid:\n\n1. Succinic acid → diethyl succinate (Fischer esterification)\n2. Diethyl succinate + 2 equiv NaOEt → intramolecular Claisen (