ent approach to the entire synthesis. What if I don't go through 1,4-cyclohexanedione at all?\n\nNew approach: Build the ring through a double Michael addition of a β-ketoester to a bis-enone derived from succinic acid.\n\nStep 1: Succinic acid → succinyl chloride (SOCl2)\nStep 2: Succinyl chloride + 2 equiv vinyl cuprate (from vinyl bromide + CuI) → divinyl ketone: CH2=CH-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH=CH2\n\nWait, this is a bis-enone! 1,7-Octadiene-3,5-dione.\n\nStep 3: 2 equiv enolate of methyl acetoacetate + bis-enone → double Michael addition → linear product\n\nStep 4: Intramolecular aldol cyclization → 6-membered ring\n\nLet me work through step 3-4.\n\nThe bis-enone: CH2=CH-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH=CH2\n\nDouble Michael addition of methyl acetoacetate enolate:\n\nCH3CO-CH⁻-COOMe + CH2=CH-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH=CH2 → CH3CO-CH(COOMe)-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CH(COOMe)-COCH3\n\nWait, that's not right. The Michael addition adds the enolate to the β-carbon of the enone:\n\nCH3CO-CH⁻-COOMe + CH2=CH-CO-R → CH3CO-CH(COOMe)-CH2-CH2-CO-R\n\nSo the double Michael addition product is:\n\nCH3CO-CH(COOMe)-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH(COOMe)-COCH3\n\nWait, that's not right either. Let me be more careful.\n\nFirst Michael addition:\nCH3CO-CH⁻-COOMe + CH2=CH-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH=CH2 → CH3CO-CH(COOMe)-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH=CH2\n\nSecond Michael addition:\nCH3CO-CH⁻-COOMe + CH3CO-CH(COOMe)-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH=CH2 → CH3CO-CH(COOMe)-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH(COOMe)-COCH3\n\nThis is a long chain: CH3CO-CH(COOMe)-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH(COOMe)-COCH3\n\nFor intramolecular aldol cyclization to a 6-membered ring:\n\nNumbering: C1(H3)-C2(=O)-C3(H)(COOMe)-C4(H2)-C5(H2)-C6(=O)-C7(H2)-C8(H2)-C9(=O)-C10(H2)-C11(H)(COOMe)-C12(=O)-C13(H3)\n\nEnolate of C1 (methyl of C2=O) attacks C9=O:\nRing: C1-C2-C3-C4-C5-C6-C7-C8-C9 → 9 atoms → 9-membered ring. Way too big.\n\nEnolate of C3 (α to C2=O) attacks C9=O:\nRing: C3-C4-C5-C6-C7-C8-C9 → 7 atoms → 7-membered ring. Still too big.\n\nEnolate of C4 (α to C6=O)