Actually, Grignard on succinic anhydride:\nFirst addition: MeMgBr attacks one carbonyl → opens the anhydride → gives a magnesium carboxylate + ketone\nSecond addition: MeMgBr attacks the ketone → gives a tertiary alcohol\n\nProduct: (CH3)2C(OH)-CH2-CH2-COO⁻MgBr → after workup: (CH3)2C(OH)-CH2-CH2-COOH\n\nThis is a hydroxy acid, not a diketone.\n\nWhat if I use a different approach? Succinyl chloride + 2 equiv Me2CuLi:\n\nMe2CuLi is a less reactive nucleophile that adds once to acyl chlorides to give ketones:\n\nSuccinyl chloride + 2 equiv Me2CuLi → CH3CO-CH2-CH2-COCH3 (1,4-butanedione, 4 carbons)\n\nThis is a 1,4-diketone, not a 1,5-diketone. For a 1,5-diketone, I'd need glutaryl chloride (5-carbon diacid chloride), which has 5 carbons.\n\nHmm, I can't make a 1,5-diketone directly from succinic acid.\n\nBut wait, what if I add a carbon to succinic acid first?\n\nSuccinic acid → cyanoethylation → 4-cyanobutanoic acid → hydrolysis → glutaric acid → glutaryl chloride → + 2 equiv Me2CuLi → 1,5-pentanedione → intramolecular aldol → 2-cyclohexen-1-one\n\nBut this gives a simple cyclohexenone, not a 1,4-cyclohexanedione.\n\nFor 1,4-cyclohexanedione, I need a 1,4-diketone that can cyclize to a 6-membered ring. But a 1,4-diketone cyclizes to a 5-membered ring (cyclopentenone), not a 6-membered ring.\n\nFor a 6-membered ring with a 1,4-diketone, I need a 2,7-octanedione (1,6-diketone):\n\nCH3CO-(CH2)4-COCH3 → intramolecular aldol → 2-cyclohexen-1-one (6-membered ring with one ketone)\n\nFor a 1,4-cyclohexanedione, I need a different precursor. Specifically, I need a 2,5-disubstituted 1,6-diketone:\n\nX-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-CH2-CH2-CO-X → intramolecular double aldol → 1,4-cyclohexanedione\n\nWait, this is a 1,3,6,8-tetraketone, which I've already considered.\n\nOK, I think the issue is that 1,4-cyclohexanedione can't be easily made from succinic acid by a simple cyclization. It requires a more elaborate synthesis.\n\nLet me just go with the following route and accept that step 1 is a